\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs22\lang9 AirspaceConverter\par
=================\par
This is a free, open source and multi-platform tool to convert between different airspace formats.  \par
\par
Can read airspace files in the following formats:  \par
  - OpenAir  \par
  - OpenAIP  \par
  - KML/KMZ  \par
\par
And the output can be done in the following formats:  \par
  - KMZ  \par
  - OpenAir  \par
  - Polish  \par
  - Garmin IMG  \par
\par
This utility can convert also SeeYou .CUP waypoint files to KMZ (for Google Earth). The conversion to IMG for Garmin devices is done using cGPSmapper.  \par
While converting to OpenAir this software estimates if the points entered are part of arcs or circumferences in order to make use of arc and circumference definitions of the OpeanAir format and so avoiding to output all points one by one.  \par
The ability to read KML/KMZ is based on the KMZ airspace files produced by Austrocontrol.  \par
AirspaceConverter is written in C++11 can be ran both on Linux and on Windows. It has a Qt user interface and Windows MFC UI as well in order to be immediately easy to use. Under Linux can also work also from command line to be usable from shell scripts.  \par
For more information's about this project: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.alus.it/AirspaceConverter }}{\fldrslt{http://www.alus.it/AirspaceConverter\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22   \par
Contributors are, as usual, warmly welcome!\par
\par
Why this software?\par
------------------\par
Airspace represented in 3D in Google Earth can help to visualize and better understand the airspace structure.\par
Not only, having the planned route or track of a flight (as GPX file), displayed as well in Google Earth will make easy to check for airspace crossed or to be avoided.  \par
This software can also be useful for maintainers of OpenAir airspace and SeeYou .CUP waypoints files, not only to visualize airspace and waypoints but also to verify the syntax of OpenAir and CUP commands entered.  \par
For the "landable" waypoints in the CUP files an estimation of the runway perimeter is drawn on the earth surface, in order to do that not only the position is used but also the runway orientation and length. This is particularly useful to verify that the position of the airfield in the CUP file matches exactly the runway in Google Earth.  In software like LK8000 the airfield position is considered as the exact center of the runway, orientation and length are used to assist for landing with an HSI and glide slope indications thus the correctness of position, orientation and length becomes really important.  \par
OpenAIP ({{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.openaip.net/ }}{\fldrslt{http://www.openaip.net/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22 ) provides a free, worldwide and updated airspace repository but in his own format, while many devices and software support OpenAir airspace files.\par
This software can convert also to OpenAir so making OpenAIP data available to many portable devices. There are also cases where the "official" airspace files are available only in KML format like the Austrian airspace from Austrocontrol, also in this case is possible to convert it to OpenAir.\par
\par
About KML format\par
----------------\par
KML, used by Google Earth is probably a good format to define models of buildings but it is not exactly practical to define airspace. This because it not possible, at least from my understanding, to define in the same 3D object points at altitudes with different references: it is the typical case of an airspace with AGL floor and AMSL ceiling.  \par
One possible solution is to translate, where necessary all the altitudes to the same reference but to do that we need the know the altitude of the terrain at every location, reason why this software uses terrain maps.  \par
Another important limitation of KML is that surfaces which follow the terrain are possible only at terrain altitude.  \par
So please, be advised that, what you will see in Google Earth will not exactly match how airspace definitions are really intended.\par
\par
LK8000 terrain raster map files\par
-------------------------------\par
This program uses the same terrain raster maps (.dem) of LK8000 to convert altitudes from AGL to AMSL.  \par
In case the loaded terrain maps are overlapping, the one with the best resolution will be automatically used.  \par
On the LK8000 website there is a wide terrain raster map collection: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.lk8000.it/download/maps.html }}{\fldrslt{http://www.lk8000.it/download/maps.html\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22   \par
The part of this program reading and using the terrain maps has been derived and adapted from LK8000 project.  \par
To know more about LK8000 project: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.lk8000.it }}{\fldrslt{http://www.lk8000.it\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22   \par
The repository of LK8000 is available here: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://github.com/LK8000/LK8000 }}{\fldrslt{https://github.com/LK8000/LK8000\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
\par
The common shared library\par
-------------------------\par
This software is designed to keep completely separated functionalities from the user interfaces.  \par
All the reading, writing and conversion features are in a common shared library: libAirspaceConverter can be compiled under different platfoms and so used from different user interfaces.\par
\par
Linux command line version\par
--------------------------\par
The Linux command line version works taking several arguments, for example:  \par
`AirspaceConverter -q 1013 -a 35 -i inputFileOpenAir.txt -i inputFileOpenAIP.aip -w waypoints.cup -m terrainMap.dem -o outputFile.kmz`  \par
\par
Possible options:  \par
  -q: optional, specify the QNH in hPa used to calculate height of flight levels  \par
  -a: optional, specify a default terrain altitude in meters to calculate AGL heights of points not covered by loaded terrain map(s)  \par
  -i: multiple, input file(s) can be OpenAir (.txt), OpenAIP (.aip)  \par
  -w: multiple, input waypoint file(s) in the SeeYou CUP format (.cup)  \par
  -m: optional, multiple, terrain map file(s) (.dem) used to lookup terrain heights  \par
  -o: optional, output file .kmz, .mp (Polish) or .txt (OpenAir) if not specified will be used the name of first input file as KMZ  \par
  -v: print version number  \par
  -h: print this guide  \par
\par
At least one input airspace or waypoint file must be present.  \par
Warning: any already existing output file will be overwritten.\par
\par
Windows MFC version\par
-------------------\par
The native Windows MFC executable needs just a couple of small DLLs: zip.dll zlib.dll to be kept in the same folder.  \par
If you get the error about VCRUNTIME140.dll missing: it can be easily and quickly fixed installing the: MS VC++ redistributable, this will allow this software to run also on older Windows versions such us WindowsXP.  \par
\par
This Windows MFC version has graphical user interface, this should be the default way to use it:\par
\par
1. Choose the desired output format\par
2. If needed, specify the QNH to be used for calculating the height of flight levels, this must be done before reading airspace files.\par
3. Specify a default terrain altitude to be used for the points not under terrain raster map coverage.\par
4. Select as input multiple OpenAir (.txt) and/or OpenAIP (.aip) files or the folder containing them.\par
5. And/or select one or multiple waypoints files (.cup) or the folder containing them.\par
6. Optionally it is possible to load multiple raster map files (.dem) with the terrain altitude.\par
7. Eventually choose a different name for the output file.\par
8. Press the button convert to start the conversion process.\par
9. Verify if the output is correct and report any problem found.\par
\par
Qt user interface\par
-----------------\par
In order to be portable, the graphical interface has been rewritten also in Qt and actually it can be compiled both under Linux and Windows.\par
\par
Disclaimer\par
----------\par
WARNING: this program is experimental. The generated output files may contains errors.\par
So please always verify the generated files before using in flight and report any error found.  \par
By using this program you understand and completely agree that the generated output files (maybe wrong) are just for demonstration purposes and they do not absolutely substitute the official AIP publications.  \par
Please always refer to official AIP publications for valid and updated airspace definitions.\par
